Problem Statement

Business Context

A sales forecast is a prediction of future sales revenue based on historical data, industry trends, and the status of the current sales pipeline. Businesses use the sales forecast to estimate weekly, monthly, quarterly, and annual sales totals. A company needs to make an accurate sales forecast as it adds value across an organization and helps the different verticals to chalk out their future course of action.

Forecasting helps an organization plan its sales operations by region and provides valuable insights to the supply chain team regarding the procurement of goods and materials. An accurate sales forecast process has many benefits which include improved decision-making about the future and reduction of sales pipeline and forecast risks. Moreover, it helps to reduce the time spent in planning territory coverage and establish benchmarks that can be used to assess trends in the future.

Objective

SuperKart is a retail chain operating supermarkets and food marts across various tier cities, offering a wide range of products. To optimize its inventory management and make informed decisions around regional sales strategies, SuperKart wants to accurately forecast the sales revenue of its outlets for the upcoming quarter.

To operationalize these insights at scale, the company has partnered with a data science firmnot just to build a predictive model based on historical sales data, but to develop and deploy a robust forecasting solution that can be integrated into SuperKarts decision-making systems and used across its network of stores.

Data Description

The data contains the different attributes of the various products and stores.The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • Product_Id - unique identifier of each product, each identifier having two letters at the beginning followed by a number.
  • Product_Weight - weight of each product
  • Product_Sugar_Content - sugar content of each product like low sugar, regular and no sugar
  • Product_Allocated_Area - ratio of the allocated display area of each product to the total display area of all the products in a store
  • Product_Type - broad category for each product like meat, snack foods, hard drinks, dairy, canned, soft drinks, health and hygiene, baking goods, bread, breakfast, frozen foods, fruits and vegetables, household, seafood, starchy foods, others
  • Product_MRP - maximum retail price of each product
  • Store_Id - unique identifier of each store
  • Store_Establishment_Year - year in which the store was established
  • Store_Size - size of the store depending on sq. feet like high, medium and low
  • Store_Location_City_Type - type of city in which the store is located like Tier 1, Tier 2 and Tier 3. Tier 1 consists of cities where the standard of living is comparatively higher than its Tier 2 and Tier 3 counterparts.
  • Store_Type - type of store depending on the products that are being sold there like Departmental Store, Supermarket Type 1, Supermarket Type 2 and Food Mart
  • Product_Store_Sales_Total - total revenue generated by the sale of that particular product in that particular store

Model Building

Define functions for Model Evaluation

In[20]:
# function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
    mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAPE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

The ML models to be built can be any two out of the following:

  1. Decision Tree
  2. Bagging
  3. Random Forest
  4. AdaBoost
  5. Gradient Boosting
  6. XGBoost

Rationale for Model Selection

We will select Random Forest and XGBoost because tree-based ensembles will perform well with structured sales data. They excel at capturing non-linear relationships (like between Price and Location) without requiring complex feature scaling.

1. Random Forest Regressor (Bagging)

  • This will be our baseline.
  • Random Forest's averaging of predictions reduces overfitting.
  • Be able to train with our features with minimal tuning.

2. XGBoost Regressor (Boosting)

  • XGBoost is well trusted to perform well.
  • XGBoost can optimize to squeeze out maximum accuracy.
  • It handles One-Hot Encoding better than standard trees.

In[22]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder, StandardScaler
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

# Identify categorical and numerical features
# Re-extract these from X_train to ensure correctness
categorical_features = X_train.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns
numerical_features = X_train.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).columns

# Create a column transformer for preprocessing
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', StandardScaler(), numerical_features),
        ('cat', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'), categorical_features)
    ])

# Create a pipeline with the preprocessor and RandomForestRegressor
rf_pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
    ('regressor', RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42))
])

# Define the parameter grid for the RandomForestRegressor within the pipeline
param_grid = {
    'regressor__n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'regressor__max_depth': [10, 20, None]
}

# Instantiate GridSearchCV
grid_search_rf = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=rf_pipeline,
    param_grid=param_grid,
    cv=3,
    scoring='r2',
    n_jobs=-1, # Use all available cores for parallel processing
    verbose=2 # Verbosity level (higher means more messages)
)

print("Starting GridSearchCV for RandomForestRegressor...")
# Fit GridSearchCV to the training data
grid_search_rf.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("\nGridSearchCV complete.")
# Print the best parameters
print("Best parameters found: ", grid_search_rf.best_params_)

# Print the best R-squared score
print("Best R-squared score: {:.4f}".format(grid_search_rf.best_score_))

Starting GridSearchCV for RandomForestRegressor...
Fitting 3 folds for each of 9 candidates, totalling 27 fits

GridSearchCV complete.
Best parameters found:  {'regressor__max_depth': 10, 'regressor__n_estimators': 300}
Best R-squared score: 0.9263

The Baseline Model Overview

Objective & Methodology To optimize the baseline Random Forest Regressor, we will use GridSearchCV with 3-fold CV.

Key Findings & Performance

  • Best Configuration: The model achieved optimal performance with n_estimators=300 and max_depth=10.
  • Score: The best cross-validated $R^2$ score was 0.9263, indicating that the model explains approximately 92.6% of the variance in the target sales data.

Insights The selection of max_depth=10 (as opposed to 20 or None) might suggest that a moderately constrained tree depth allows the model to train without overfitting.

# 1. Identify categorical and numerical features

numerical_features = X_train.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).columns

# 2. Create a column transformer for preprocessing
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', StandardScaler(), numerical_features),
        ('cat', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'), categorical_features)
    ])

# 3. Create a pipeline with the preprocessor and XGBRegressor
xgb_pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
    ('regressor', XGBRegressor(random_state=42)) # Using a fixed random_state for reproducibility
])

# 4. Define the parameter grid for the XGBRegressor within the pipeline
param_grid_xgb = {
    'regressor__n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'regressor__max_depth': [3, 5, 7]
}

# 5. Instantiate GridSearchCV
grid_search_xgb = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=xgb_pipeline,
    param_grid=param_grid_xgb,
    cv=3, # Using 3-fold cross-validation
    scoring='r2', # Using R-squared as the scoring metric
    n_jobs=-1, # Use all available cores for parallel processing
    verbose=2 # Verbosity level (higher means more messages)
)

print("Starting GridSearchCV for XGBRegressor...")

grid_search_xgb.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Best parameters found: ", grid_search_xgb.best_params_)

print("Best R-squared score: {:.4f}".format(grid_search_xgb.best_score_))

    ])

# Create a pipeline with the preprocessor and XGBRegressor
xgb_pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
    ('regressor', XGBRegressor(random_state=42)) # Using a fixed random_state for reproducibility
])

# Instantiate GridSearchCV with the advanced parameter grid
grid_search_xgb_advanced = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=xgb_pipeline,
    param_grid=param_grid_xgb_advanced,
    cv=3, # Using 3-fold cross-validation
    scoring='r2', # Using R-squared as the scoring metric
    n_jobs=-1, # Use all available cores for parallel processing
    verbose=2 # Verbosity level (higher means more messages)
)

print("Starting advanced GridSearchCV for XGBRegressor...")
# Fit GridSearchCV to the training data
grid_search_xgb_advanced.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("\nAdvanced GridSearchCV complete for XGBRegressor.")

expected_columns = [

app_code = f"""
import os
import joblib
import pandas as pd
from flask import Flask, request, jsonify

app = Flask(__name__)

# Load the model (assumes it is in the same folder as app.py inside the container)
try:
    model = joblib.load('best_model.pkl')
    print("Model loaded successfully.")
except Exception as e:
    print(f"Error loading model: {{e}}")
    model = None

@app.route('/')
def home():
    return "SuperKart Sales Prediction API is Live!"

@app.route('/predict', methods=['POST'])
def predict():
    if not model:
        return jsonify({{'error': 'Model failed to load'}}), 500

    try:
        data = request.get_json()
        if not data:
            return jsonify({{'error': 'No input data provided'}}), 400

        # Create DataFrame ensuring columns are in the correct order
        # We explicitly use the expected columns list injected during file creation
        columns = {expected_columns}

        # Handle single dict or list of dicts
        if isinstance(data, dict):
            df = pd.DataFrame([data], columns=columns)
        else:
            df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=columns)

        prediction = model.predict(df)
        return jsonify({{'prediction': prediction.tolist()}})

    except Exception as e:
        return jsonify({{'error': str(e)}}), 500

if __name__ == '__main__':
    # Run on port 7860 for Hugging Face Spaces
    app.run(host='0.0.0.0', port=7860)
"""

# Write the file
with open('backend_files/app.py', 'w') as f:
    f.write(app_code)
print("Created 'backend_files/app.py'")

Analyzing Feature Importances

To gain more insight, we will extract feature importances from the best Random Forest model, visualize the top most important features, and cover top sales drivers, store location/type impact, and strategies for inventory, pricing, and expansion based on these importances and insights from the EDA.

In[91]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd

# 1. Access the best Random Forest model from grid_search_rf
best_rf_model_pipeline = grid_search_rf.best_estimator_

# 2. Extract feature importances from the 'regressor' step
feature_importances = best_rf_model_pipeline.named_steps['regressor'].feature_importances_

# 3. Obtain the names of the features generated by the preprocessor step
# Access the preprocessor step from the best pipeline
preprocessor = best_rf_model_pipeline.named_steps['preprocessor']

# Get feature names after preprocessing (including one-hot encoded categorical features)
# Ensure that the ColumnTransformer is fitted to X_train before calling get_feature_names_out
# This should already be handled by the grid_search_rf.fit(X_train, y_train) step
all_feature_names = preprocessor.get_feature_names_out()

# 4. Create a Pandas DataFrame with Feature and Importance
feature_importance_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature': all_feature_names,
    'Importance': feature_importances
})

# 5. Sort the DataFrame in descending order
feature_importance_df = feature_importance_df.sort_values(by='Importance', ascending=False)

# 6. Select the top 20 most important features
top_features = feature_importance_df.head(20)

# 7. Create a horizontal bar plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.barplot(x='Importance', y='Feature', data=top_features, palette='viridis')
plt.title('Top 10 Most Important Features', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Importance', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Feature', fontsize=12)
plt.tight_layout()

# 8. Display the plot
plt.show()

After end-to-end analysisfrom data exploration to training a Random Forest model with 93% accuracy ($R^2$)we have identified the key drivers of sales revenue for SuperKart.

Key Drivers of Sales (Actionable Insights)

Our model reveals that Product Price/Weight and Store Type/Location are the some of the strongest predictors of revenue, outweighing product type.

  • The single most important predictor of sales is the product's price (Product_MRP or Maximum Retail Price). Higher-priced items drive higher total revenue than low-cost volume items.
  • Surprisingly, Product_Weight is the second most important feature. This suggests that bulkier/heavier items are significant revenue contributors. (These could be bulk packs)
  • Store type and city tier seems to be a strong factor as well. It might be worth it to explore store type and city/location relations with the data to understand what is actionable there.

Business Recommendations

Based on these findings, we propose the following strategies for SuperKart:

Initiate Inventory Optimizations

  • Utilize this UI to orient stocking with which stores are the most effective at selling them. This information can be learned from the model.

Monitor the Model's Accuracy

  • Add reliable model monitoring to ensure the accuracy of the model so you can build business functions based on the model results.

Improve Model's Integrations

  • This model's ability to predict pricing at scale can become very powerful and relevant to the success of every individual store across the world. Initiate Business automations based on model predictions like:
    • Distribution System's Inventory Optimization automation - distribution systems can now use the prediction of which products do well at which types of stores and automate the decisions on which products to stock up on.
    • Automate Product Catalog Expansions - Model can determine the success of new products

Increase Revenue: Pricing & Bundling

  • Since higher MRP correlates with higher revenue, customers are willing to pay for value.
  • Introduce Product Bundling. For example, instead of selling single units of "Soft Drinks" promote "Family Packs" or bulk bundles. This leverages the two top features to drive up the transaction value.
